                        <collation>
                           <p>
									14 quires: i12 (folios 1-12), ii10 (folios 13-22), iii6 (folios 23-28), iv-xiii10 (folios 29-137), xiv8 (folios 138-145).  
								</p>
                        </collation>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>
                           <p>Columns: 2;
                                                  ruled lines: 25;
                                                  written lines: 25; Four blank lines are found between any two books. The beginning of each pericope is marked in the margin by a large ornamental letter samekh. Each pericope is divided into 7 subsections, numbered in Hebrew letters in the margin. The masorah magna occupies 3 to 5 lines in the upper and 3 to 6 lines in the lower margin. Numerous masoretic rubrics at the end of each book of the Torah, as well as at the end of the whole Pentateuch. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <scriptDesc>
                     <scriptNote>Yemenite square script, punctuate, of the 15th century. David ben Benayah ben Sa'adyah ben Zekhariah, inscribed with his name in the colophon on folio 144r.</scriptNote>
